One useful feature from SublimeText that need to get inside VScode: the ability to define an option to open a type of file with a specific soft.

For example, if I try on a png file, it will allow me to open it in Photoshop.

![](https://files.not.live/Capture_decran_2016-09-19_a_02.31.05.jpg)

This is set through global configuration files like this : 

```
[
    {"id": "side-bar-files-open-with",
        "children":
        [
            //application 1
            {
                "caption": "Photoshop",
                "id": "side-bar-files-open-with-photoshop",

                "command": "side_bar_files_open_with",
                "args": {
                    "paths": [],
                    "application": "Adobe Photoshop CC 2015.5.app", // OSX
                    "extensions":"psd|png|jpg|jpeg",  //any file with these extensions
                    "args":[]
                },
                "open_automatically" : false // will close the view/tab and launch the application
            },

            {
                "caption": "Illustrator",
                "id": "side-bar-files-open-with-illustrator",

                "command": "side_bar_files_open_with",
                "args": {
                    "paths": [],
                    "application": "Adobe Illustrator CC 2015.3.app", // OSX
                    "extensions":"ai|svg",  //any file with these extensions
                    "args":[]
                },
                "open_automatically" : false // will close the view/tab and launch the application
            },

            //separator
            {"caption":"-"},
            //application n
            {
                "caption": "Chrome",
                "id": "side-bar-files-open-with-chrome",

                "command": "side_bar_files_open_with",
                "args": {
                    "paths": [],
                    "application": "C:\\Documents and Settings\\tito\\local\\Datos de programa\\Google\\Chrome\\Application\\chrome.exe",
                    "extensions":".*", //any file with extension
                    "args":[]
                },
                "open_automatically" : false // will close the view/tab and launch the application
            },

            {"caption":"-"}
        ]
    }
]
```

There is definitely something to get from this (and maybe an even more easy way?).

Thanks.

- VSCode Version: 1.5.2
- OS Version: OS X

Steps to Reproduce:

**package.json:**

``` json
{
  "devDependencies": {
    "@types/jasmine": "^2.2.33",
    "typescript": "^2.0.2"
  }
}
```

**tsconfig.json:**

``` json
{
    "include": [
        "./test.ts"
    ]
}
```

**test.ts:**

``` ts
describe('code', () => {
    it('should know that describe and it are defined', () => {
        expect(true).toBeTruthy();
    })
})
```

**.vscode/settings.json:**

``` json
{
    "typescript.tsdk": "./node_modules/typescript/lib"
}
```

![gif](http://g.recordit.co/5ZCckiKVJX.gif)

Expected: vscode understands global/ambient types from `node_modules/@types` just like tsc does
Actual: vscode does not understand global/ambient types from `node_modules/@types`

- VSCode Version: 1.5.2
- OS Version: win10

I created a extension, which registers a new Statusbar Item with call to [createStatusbarItem](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/extensionAPI/vscode-api). Setting property command to e.g 'editor.action.commentLine'. After click the message "Command 'Toggle Line Comment' can not be run from here." 
![error](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/13434739/18615003/df6e9f62-7d9a-11e6-9fac-3835f1c19c18.png)

The issue happens since v1.5.1.

Steps to Reproduce:

[comment-line.zip](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/files/478634/comment-line.zip)
1. Unzip extension comment-line
2. npm install
3. execute extension
4. click on created StatusBarItem 

Code needed to reproduce issue:

`export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
   const statusBarItem = vscode.window.createStatusBarItem(vscode.StatusBarAlignment.Left, 1);
    statusBarItem.command = 'editor.action.commentLine';
    statusBarItem.text = '//';
    statusBarItem.show();
    context.subscriptions.push(statusBarItem);
}`
